faqSchema:
  - question: "What is the FERS supplement and how does it work?"
    answer: "The FERS supplement is a special payment designed to bridge the income gap between when you retire and when you become eligible for Social Security at age 62. It approximates the Social Security benefit you earned during your FERS-covered employment. You only qualify for the supplement if you retire at your Minimum Retirement Age (MRA) with 30 years of service, or at age 60 with 20 years of service. The supplement is subject to an earnings test similar to Social Security — if you have substantial earned income from working, your supplement may be reduced or eliminated. The supplement automatically ends when you turn 62, regardless of whether you actually claim Social Security at that time."
  - question: "How does WEP affect federal employees?"
    answer: "The Windfall Elimination Provision (WEP) can reduce Social Security benefits for workers who receive a pension from employment not covered by Social Security. For FERS employees, this primarily applies if you have previous employment where you didn't pay Social Security taxes (such as certain state/local government jobs or foreign employment), or if you have time under the old Civil Service Retirement System (CSRS). Pure FERS employees who have always paid Social Security taxes throughout their careers are generally NOT affected by WEP. If you do have non-covered employment, the WEP reduction depends on how many years of substantial earnings you have under Social Security — having 30 or more years of substantial earnings eliminates the WEP reduction entirely."
  - question: "When should I claim Social Security as a FERS employee?"
    answer: "The optimal claiming age depends on your individual situation. You can claim as early as 62 (with a permanent reduction), wait until your Full Retirement Age (66-67 depending on birth year) for your full benefit, or delay until age 70 for an 8% annual increase. Because FERS employees already have a guaranteed pension (FERS annuity), you may have more flexibility than private sector workers. Delaying Social Security can make sense if you're healthy and expect longevity, especially since the higher benefit is inflation-adjusted for life. We model your specific situation — including your FERS annuity amount, TSP balance, health, and life expectancy — to determine which claiming strategy maximizes your lifetime income."
  - question: "How do FERS and Social Security work together in retirement?"
    answer: "FERS was designed as a three-part retirement system: FERS annuity, Social Security, and TSP. Your FERS annuity begins when you retire and continues for life. Social Security can start anytime from age 62 to 70, and also continues for life with annual cost-of-living adjustments. Together, these provide a foundation of guaranteed lifetime income. You then supplement with TSP withdrawals as needed. Both your FERS annuity and Social Security are taxable income (though the portion of Social Security that's taxable depends on your total income). Strategic planning involves coordinating the timing of Social Security, managing TSP withdrawals tax-efficiently, and ensuring your combined income supports your lifestyle without pushing you into higher tax brackets or triggering Medicare IRMAA surcharges."
  - question: "Will my spouse's Social Security benefits be affected by GPO?"
    answer: "The Government Pension Offset (GPO) can reduce Social Security spousal or survivor benefits if you receive a pension from government employment not covered by Social Security. Similar to WEP, this primarily affects employees with CSRS service or other non-covered government employment. FERS employees who have always paid Social Security taxes are generally not subject to GPO. If GPO does apply, it can reduce spousal or survivor benefits by two-thirds of your government pension amount. Understanding whether GPO affects your situation is important for couples planning survivor income and coordinating spousal benefits."
