    <!-- WEP/GPO ELIMINATED -->
    <section id="wep-gpo-eliminated" class="fed-ed-ss-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER III: GOOD NEWS</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-ss-section-title">WEP and GPO <em>Eliminated</em></h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">Effective January 1, 2025, the Windfall Elimination Provision (WEP) and Government Pension Offset (GPO) were permanently eliminated. This is huge news for federal employees who were previously affected by these complex and often unfair reductions to Social Security benefits.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-good-news-card">
        <h3 class="fed-ed-good-news-title">
          <svg class="fed-ed-good-news-icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
            <path d="M22 11.08V12a10 10 0 1 1-5.93-9.14"/>
            <polyline points="22,4 12,14.01 9,11.01"/>
          </svg>
          What This Means for Federal Employees
        </h3>
        <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6; margin: 1rem 0;">
          <li><strong>WEP Elimination:</strong> If you had previous non-covered government employment, your Social Security benefits are no longer reduced</li>
          <li><strong>GPO Elimination:</strong> Spousal and survivor Social Security benefits are no longer offset by your federal pension</li>
          <li><strong>Full Benefits:</strong> You receive your complete Social Security benefit based on your earnings record</li>
          <li><strong>Retroactive Relief:</strong> Current retirees affected by WEP/GPO received retroactive payments and benefit adjustments</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Before vs. After WEP/GPO Elimination</h3>
        
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 3rem;">
          <div>
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Before (Pre-2025)</h4>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6; list-style: none; padding: 0;">
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">× Social Security benefits reduced by up to $512/month (WEP)</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">× Spousal benefits reduced by 2/3 of government pension (GPO)</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">× Complex calculations and exceptions</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0;">× Many affected retirees unaware of impact</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          
          <div>
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #10B981; margin-bottom: 1rem;">After (2025+)</h4>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6; list-style: none; padding: 0;">
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Full Social Security benefits based on earnings record</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Full spousal and survivor benefits available</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid #f3f4f6;">✓ Simplified planning and calculations</li>
              <li style="padding: 0.5rem 0;">✓ Significantly higher retirement income for many</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">This change is particularly beneficial for federal employees with mixed careers — those who worked in the private sector, state/local government, or had military service before federal employment. Previously complex calculations are now straightforward: you get your full Social Security benefit based on your complete earnings history.</p>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">Current federal retirees who were receiving reduced benefits received automatic adjustments and retroactive payments. If you retired before 2025 and were affected by WEP or GPO, your benefits were automatically corrected.</p>
    </section>
    
    <!-- CLAIMING STRATEGY -->
    <section id="claiming-strategy" class="fed-ed-ss-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER IV: TIMING</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-ss-section-title">Optimal <em>Claiming</em> Strategy</h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">Federal employees have unique flexibility in Social Security timing because you already have guaranteed pension income from FERS. This allows you to potentially delay Social Security for higher benefits without relying solely on investments for income.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-claiming-ages">
        <div class="fed-ed-claiming-age">
          <div class="fed-ed-claiming-age-number">62</div>
          <div class="fed-ed-claiming-age-label">Earliest Age</div>
          <p class="fed-ed-claiming-age-desc">Permanently reduced benefits. May make sense if you need income or have health concerns.</p>
          <div class="fed-ed-claiming-age-benefit">75% of Full Benefit</div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="fed-ed-claiming-age">
          <div class="fed-ed-claiming-age-number">66-67</div>
          <div class="fed-ed-claiming-age-label">Full Retirement Age</div>
          <p class="fed-ed-claiming-age-desc">Full benefit amount based on your earnings record. No reduction or credit.</p>
          <div class="fed-ed-claiming-age-benefit">100% of Full Benefit</div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="fed-ed-claiming-age optimal">
          <div class="fed-ed-claiming-age-number">70</div>
          <div class="fed-ed-claiming-age-label">Maximum Age</div>
          <p class="fed-ed-claiming-age-desc">Maximum benefit with delayed retirement credits. Often optimal for federal retirees.</p>
          <div class="fed-ed-claiming-age-benefit">132% of Full Benefit</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Federal Employee Claiming Considerations</h3>
        
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 3rem;">
          <div>
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Reasons to Claim Early (62)</h4>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6;">
              <li>Need the income immediately</li>
              <li>Health concerns affect longevity</li>
              <li>Want to start benefits while FERS supplement still active</li>
              <li>Spouse optimization strategies</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          
          <div>
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #F09F54; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Reasons to Delay to 70</h4>
            <ul style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6;">
              <li>FERS annuity provides sufficient income</li>
              <li>Good health and family longevity</li>
              <li>Want maximum inflation-protected benefit</li>
              <li>Tax diversification with TSP withdrawals</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">The 8% annual increase for delaying Social Security from Full Retirement Age to 70 is a guaranteed, inflation-adjusted return that's hard to beat. For federal employees with secure FERS income, this delay often makes financial sense if health and longevity support it.</p>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">Key insight: Unlike private sector workers who might need Social Security income immediately upon retirement, federal employees can often afford to optimize timing because they have predictable FERS annuity income throughout retirement.</p>
    </section>
    
    <!-- COORDINATION -->
    <section id="coordination" class="fed-ed-ss-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER V: INTEGRATION</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-ss-section-title">FERS and Social Security <em>Coordination</em></h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">FERS was designed as a three-legged stool: FERS annuity, Social Security, and TSP. Understanding how these pieces work together is essential for optimizing your total retirement income and minimizing taxes.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">The Federal Retirement Income Stack</h3>
        
        <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr)); gap: 2rem; margin-top: 2rem;">
          <div style="text-align: center; padding: 2rem; background: #f8f9fb; border-radius: 12px;">
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">FERS Annuity</h4>
            <p style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Guaranteed monthly income starting at retirement. Includes annual COLAs for inflation protection.</p>
            <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); color: #F09F54; font-size: 0.8rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em;">Immediate Income</div>
          </div>
          
          <div style="text-align: center; padding: 2rem; background: #f8f9fb; border-radius: 12px;">
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Social Security</h4>
            <p style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Inflation-adjusted income starting at 62-70. Timing choice affects lifetime benefits significantly.</p>
            <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); color: #F09F54; font-size: 0.8rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em;">Optimizable Timing</div>
          </div>
          
          <div style="text-align: center; padding: 2rem; background: #f8f9fb; border-radius: 12px;">
            <h4 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">TSP Withdrawals</h4>
            <p style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Flexible withdrawals to fill income gaps and provide tax diversification options.</p>
            <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); color: #F09F54; font-size: 0.8rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.05em;">Flexible Supplement</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">Strategic coordination involves timing Social Security to maximize lifetime benefits while using TSP withdrawals to bridge any income gaps. This approach allows you to optimize each income stream individually while maintaining your desired lifestyle throughout retirement.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-stats-grid">
        <div class="fed-ed-stat">
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-number">40%</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-label">FERS Annuity of Total Income</span>
        </div>
        <div class="fed-ed-stat">
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-number">30%</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-label">Social Security of Total Income</span>
        </div>
        <div class="fed-ed-stat">
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-number">30%</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-stat-label">TSP of Total Income</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">Both FERS annuity and Social Security are fully taxable as ordinary income (though Social Security may be partially taxable depending on your total income). Strategic TSP withdrawals can help manage your tax bracket and avoid triggering higher taxes on Social Security benefits.</p>
    </section>
    
    <!-- SPOUSAL STRATEGY -->
    <section id="spouse-strategy" class="fed-ed-ss-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER VI: SPOUSAL COORDINATION</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-ss-section-title">Married Couples <em>Strategy</em></h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">Married federal employees have additional Social Security strategies available, including spousal benefits and survivor planning. With WEP/GPO eliminated, these strategies are now straightforward and potentially very valuable.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Spousal Social Security Strategies</h3>
        
        <table class="fed-ed-comparison-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Strategy</th>
              <th>When to Use</th>
              <th>Key Benefit</th>
              <th>Considerations</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Spousal Benefits</strong></td>
              <td>Lower-earning spouse</td>
              <td>Up to 50% of higher earner's benefit</td>
              <td>Must wait until higher earner claims</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="highlight">
              <td><strong>Survivor Benefits</strong></td>
              <td>When one spouse dies</td>
              <td>100% of deceased spouse's benefit</td>
              <td>Critical for FERS + SS coordination</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Claiming Coordination</strong></td>
              <td>Different optimal ages</td>
              <td>Maximize household lifetime benefits</td>
              <td>May involve one early, one delayed</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">With GPO eliminated, federal employee spouses can now receive full spousal and survivor Social Security benefits without reduction. This significantly improves retirement security for federal families, especially when combined with FERS survivor annuity elections.</p>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">Survivor planning is particularly important for federal couples because the surviving spouse loses the FERS annuity (unless survivor benefits were elected) but can inherit the higher of the two Social Security benefits. This affects both Social Security claiming timing and FERS survivor benefit elections.</p>
    </section>
    
    <!-- OPTIMIZATION -->
    <section id="optimization" class="fed-ed-ss-section">
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER VII: TAX OPTIMIZATION</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-ss-section-title">Social Security <em>Tax</em> Planning</h2>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">Social Security benefits can be taxable depending on your total income, and federal employees with multiple income sources (FERS, Social Security, TSP) need strategic planning to minimize taxes throughout retirement.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-glass-card">
        <h3 style="font-family: var(--font-serif-display); color: #003870; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Social Security Taxation Thresholds</h3>
        
        <table class="fed-ed-comparison-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Filing Status</th>
              <th>Income Range</th>
              <th>Taxable SS Percentage</th>
              <th>Federal Tax Strategy</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Single</strong></td>
              <td>Under $25,000</td>
              <td>0%</td>
              <td>Very low income scenario</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Single</strong></td>
              <td>$25,000 - $34,000</td>
              <td>50%</td>
              <td>Moderate FERS + TSP withdrawals</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="highlight">
              <td><strong>Single</strong></td>
              <td>Over $34,000</td>
              <td>85%</td>
              <td>Most federal retirees with FERS</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Married Filing Jointly</strong></td>
              <td>Under $32,000</td>
              <td>0%</td>
              <td>Very low income scenario</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Married Filing Jointly</strong></td>
              <td>$32,000 - $44,000</td>
              <td>50%</td>
              <td>Strategic income management zone</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="highlight">
              <td><strong>Married Filing Jointly</strong></td>
              <td>Over $44,000</td>
              <td>85%</td>
              <td>Most federal couples with FERS</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">Most federal retirees will have 85% of their Social Security benefits taxable due to their FERS annuity income. However, strategic TSP withdrawal management can help optimize total tax burden and potentially qualify for lower capital gains rates on investment income.</p>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-warning-card">
        <h3 class="fed-ed-warning-title">
          <svg class="fed-ed-warning-icon" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
            <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/>
            <line x1="12" y1="8" x2="12" y2="12"/>
            <line x1="12" y1="16" x2="12.01" y2="16"/>
          </svg>
          Medicare IRMAA Considerations
        </h3>
        <p style="font-family: var(--font-body); color: #64748b; line-height: 1.6;">High-income federal retirees may face Medicare Income-Related Monthly Adjustment Amounts (IRMAA) surcharges on Medicare premiums. Strategic timing of Social Security, TSP withdrawals, and Roth conversions can help manage modified adjusted gross income to avoid or minimize these surcharges.</p>
      </div>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">Advanced strategy: Federal employees with both traditional and Roth TSP balances have opportunities for tax optimization. By coordinating Social Security timing with strategic Roth TSP withdrawals (tax-free) and traditional TSP withdrawals (taxable), you can potentially manage your tax bracket throughout retirement.</p>
      
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">The elimination of WEP and GPO makes Social Security planning much simpler for federal employees — you get your full benefit, and you can focus on optimizing timing and tax management rather than navigating complex reduction formulas.</p>
    </section>
  </main>
</section>

<!-- FAQ SECTION -->
<section class="fed-ed-faq">
  <div class="fed-ed-faq-inner">
    <div>
      <span class="fed-ed-chapter-label">CHAPTER VIII: COMMON QUESTIONS</span>
      <h2 class="fed-ed-ss-section-title">Social Security <em>FAQ</em></h2>
      <p class="fed-ed-ss-body">Everything you need to know about Social Security as a federal employee.</p>
      <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">
        <a href="/contact/" class="fed-ed-btn-primary">Optimize My Strategy</a>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="fed-ed-faq-accordion">
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">What is the FERS supplement and how does it work?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">The FERS supplement is a special payment designed to bridge the income gap between when you retire and when you become eligible for Social Security at age 62. It approximates the Social Security benefit you earned during your FERS-covered employment. You only qualify for the supplement if you retire at your Minimum Retirement Age (MRA) with 30 years of service, or at age 60 with 20 years of service. The supplement is subject to an earnings test similar to Social Security — if you have substantial earned income from working, your supplement may be reduced or eliminated. The supplement automatically ends when you turn 62, regardless of whether you actually claim Social Security at that time.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">How does WEP affect federal employees?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">The Windfall Elimination Provision (WEP) can reduce Social Security benefits for workers who receive a pension from employment not covered by Social Security. For FERS employees, this primarily applies if you have previous employment where you didn't pay Social Security taxes (such as certain state/local government jobs or foreign employment), or if you have time under the old Civil Service Retirement System (CSRS). Pure FERS employees who have always paid Social Security taxes throughout their careers are generally NOT affected by WEP. If you do have non-covered employment, the WEP reduction depends on how many years of substantial earnings you have under Social Security — having 30 or more years of substantial earnings eliminates the WEP reduction entirely.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">When should I claim Social Security as a FERS employee?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">The optimal claiming age depends on your individual situation. You can claim as early as 62 (with a permanent reduction), wait until your Full Retirement Age (66-67 depending on birth year) for your full benefit, or delay until age 70 for an 8% annual increase. Because FERS employees already have a guaranteed pension (FERS annuity), you may have more flexibility than private sector workers. Delaying Social Security can make sense if you're healthy and expect longevity, especially since the higher benefit is inflation-adjusted for life. We model your specific situation — including your FERS annuity amount, TSP balance, health, and life expectancy — to determine which claiming strategy maximizes your lifetime income.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">How do FERS and Social Security work together in retirement?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">FERS was designed as a three-part retirement system: FERS annuity, Social Security, and TSP. Your FERS annuity begins when you retire and continues for life. Social Security can start anytime from age 62 to 70, and also continues for life with annual cost-of-living adjustments. Together, these provide a foundation of guaranteed lifetime income. You then supplement with TSP withdrawals as needed. Both your FERS annuity and Social Security are taxable income (though the portion of Social Security that's taxable depends on your total income). Strategic planning involves coordinating the timing of Social Security, managing TSP withdrawals tax-efficiently, and ensuring your combined income supports your lifestyle without pushing you into higher tax brackets or triggering Medicare IRMAA surcharges.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div class="fed-ed-faq-item">
        <button class="fed-ed-faq-trigger">
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-question">Will my spouse's Social Security benefits be affected by GPO?</span>
          <span class="fed-ed-faq-icon">+</span>
        </button>
        <div class="fed-ed-faq-panel">
          <p class="fed-ed-faq-answer">The Government Pension Offset (GPO) can reduce Social Security spousal or survivor benefits if you receive a pension from government employment not covered by Social Security. Similar to WEP, this primarily affects employees with CSRS service or other non-covered government employment. FERS employees who have always paid Social Security taxes are generally not subject to GPO. If GPO does apply, it can reduce spousal or survivor benefits by two-thirds of your government pension amount. Understanding whether GPO affects your situation is important for couples planning survivor income and coordinating spousal benefits.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<script>
(function() {
  document.querySelectorAll('.fed-ed-faq-trigger').forEach(function(btn) {
    btn.addEventListener('click', function() {
      var item = this.closest('.fed-ed-faq-item');
      var isOpen = item.classList.contains('active');
      
      // Close all items
      document.querySelectorAll('.fed-ed-faq-item').forEach(function(el) {
        el.classList.remove('active');
      });
      
      // Open clicked item if it wasn't already open
      if (!isOpen) {
        item.classList.add('active');
      }
    });
  });
  
  // Smooth scroll for navigation links
  document.querySelectorAll('.fed-ed-ss-nav a').forEach(function(link) {
    link.addEventListener('click', function(e) {
      e.preventDefault();
      const targetId = this.getAttribute('href');
      const targetElement = document.querySelector(targetId);
      if (targetElement) {
        targetElement.scrollIntoView({
          behavior: 'smooth',
          block: 'start'
        });
      }
    });
  });
})();
</script>